ngostura''  ||  {{BRA}}  || TBD || December 2022 (expected)<ref name=\"LAAD\"/> || TBD || Itagua\u00ed\n|}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Scorpene cg.svg|Image of Scorp\u00e8ne submarine\nFile:Tun Razak.JPG|Royal Malaysian Navy's submarine at a Navantia shipyard prior to delivery\nFile:S40 Riachuelo.jpg|Launching of the Brazilian submarine ''Riachuelo'', Scorp\u00e8ne class\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submarine classes in service]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TpFLG8yMmEI Scorpene SUBTICS in action]\n* [http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=427 Scorp\u00e8ne Diesel-Electric Patrol Submarine (Navy recognition)]\n* [http://www.naval-technology.com/projects/scorpene/ Naval Technology - Scorp\u00e8ne description]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/europe/scorpene.htm Global Security - Scorp\u00e8ne]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scorpene class submarine}}\n[[Category:Submarine classes]]\n[[Category:Scorp\u00e8ne-class submarines]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|sclass=2}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=INS Khanderi at sea.jpg\n|Ship caption=[[Indian Navy]]'s {{INS|Khanderi|2017|6}} at sea\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=Scorp\u00e8ne class\n|Builders=* [[DCNS (company)|DCNS]]\n* [[Navantia]]\n* [[Mazagon Dock Limited]]\n* [[Brazilian Navy|Brazilian Navy Shipyard]]\n|Operators=* {{Navy|Chile}}\n* {{Navy|Malaysia}}\n* {{Navy|India}}\n* {{Flagicon image|Naval Jack of Brazil.svg|size=23px}} [[Brazilian Navy]]\n|Class before={{sclass-|Agosta|submarine|4}}\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=* {{sclass-|Kalvari|submarine|4||2015}}\n* CA-2000\n* CM-2000\n* AM-2000\n* S-BR\n|Cost= US$450 million\n|Built range=1999\u2013present\n|In service range=   \n|In commission range=2005\u2013present\n|Total ships building= 5\n|Total ships active=  6\n|Total ships planned= 18\n|Total ships completed= 9\n|Total ships cancelled= 4\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=  \n|Ship type=[[Submarine]]\n|Ship displacement=* {{convert|1,565|t|LT|lk=on|abbr=on}} (CM-2000)\n* {{convert|1,870|t|LT|abbr=on}} (AM-2000)\n* {{convert|2000|t|LT|abbr=on}} (S-BR)<ref name=\"defpro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defpro.com/daily/details/585/ |title=First Steel Cut for Brazilian Submarine Programme |author=Nicolas von Kospot |date=2 June 2010 |publisher=www.defpro.com |accessdate=7 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717063952/http://www.defpro.com/daily/details/585/ |archivedate=July 17, 2011 }}</ref>\n|Ship length=* {{convert|61.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}} (CM-2000)\n* {{convert|70|m|ftin|abbr=on}} (AM-2000)\n* {{convert|75|m|ftin|abbr=on}} (S-BR)<ref name=\"defpro\" />\n|Ship beam= {{convert|6.2|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught= {{convert|5.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft= {{convert|5.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion= * Diesel-electric \n* Batteries\n* [[Air-independent propulsion]] (AIP)\n** MESMA AIP (DCNS models)\n** [[Defence Research and Development Organisation|DRDO]] [[Phosphoric acid fuel cell|PAFC Fuel Cell]] AIP (''Kalvari'' class)\n|Ship speed=* {{convert|20|kn|lk=in}} (submerged)\n* {{convert|12|kn|abbr=on}} (surfaced) {{cn|date=February 2020}}\n|Ship range=* {{convert|6500|nmi|km|abbr=on}} at {{convert|8|kn|abbr=on}} (surfaced)\n* {{convert|550|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|5|kn|abbr=on}} (submerged)\n|Ship endurance=* 40 days (compact)\n* 50 days (normal)\n* 50 + 21 days (AIP) \n|Ship test depth=>{{convert|350|m|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.dcnsgroup.com/naval/products/scorpene |title=Scorpene\u00ae 1000 |publisher=DCNS |accessdate=24 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915164804/http://en.dcnsgroup.com/naval/products/scorpene/ |archivedate=15 September 2014 }}</ref>\n|Ship complement= 31\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament= 6 \u00d7 {{convert|533|mm|in|abbr=on|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s for 18 [[Black Shark Torpedo|Whitehead Alenia Sistemi Subacquei Black Shark]] heavyweight torpedoes and [[Exocet|SM-39 Exocet]] anti-ship missiles and 30 [[Naval mine|mines]] in place of torpedoes\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Scorp\u00e8ne-class submarines''' are a class of [[diesel-electric]] [[attack submarine]]s jointly developed by the [[France|French]] [[Direction des Constructions Navales]] (DCNS) and the [[Spain|Spanish]] company [[Navantia]], and now by [[Naval Group]]. It features diesel propulsion and an additional [[air-independent propulsion]] (AIP).\n\n==Scorp\u00e8ne characteristics==\nThe Scorp\u00e8ne class of submarines has four subtypes:<ref name=\"Forecast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forecastinternational.com/samples/f673_completesample.pdf/ |title=The Market for Submarines |date=August 2009 |publisher=Forecast International |accessdate=13 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417114703/http://www.forecastinternational.com/samples/f673_completesample.pdf |archivedate=April 17, 2012 }}</ref> the CM-2000 conventional diesel-electric version, the AM-2000 [[air-independent propulsion]] (AIP) derivative, the downsized CA-2000 coastal submarine, and the enlarged S-BR for the [[Brazilian Navy]], without AIP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval.com.br/blog/tag/scorpene/ |title=Novas pistas sobre o 'S-BR', o novo submarino convencional Brasileiro |date=6 May 2010 |publisher=www.naval.com.br |accessdate=13 May 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100422024006/http://www.naval.com.br/blog/tag/scorpene/ |archivedate=22 April 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe Chilean and Malaysian boats are fitted with the TSM 2233 [[Thomson-CSF|Mk 2]] sonar. The class can also be fitted with an 'S-Cube' sonar suite from [[Thales Group|Thales]].<ref name=\"bharat-rakshak.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/NAVY/Scorpene.html |url-status=dead |title=Project 75 \u2013 Scorpene SSK |work= bharat-rakshak.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330082622/http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/NAVY/Scorpene.html |archive-date=30 March 2009 |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Air-independent propulsion===\nThe French Module d'Energie Sous-Marine Autonome (MESMA) system is being offered by the French shipyard [[Direction des Constructions Navales]] (DCNS) for the Scorp\u00e8ne-class submarines. It is essentially a modified version of their nuclear propulsion system with heat being generated by [[ethanol]] and oxygen. The combustion of the ethanol and stored oxygen, at a pressure of {{convert|60|atm|MPa|abbr=on}}, generates steam which powers a conventional turbine power plant. This pressure-firing allows exhaust carbon dioxide to be expelled overboard at any depth without an exhaust compressor.\n\nEach MESMA system costs around US$50\u201360 million. As installed on the Scorp\u00e8nes, it requires adding a new {{convert|8.3|m|ft|adj=on}}, 305-tonne hull section to the submarines, and enables a submarine to operate for more than 21 days under water, depending on variables such as speed.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}\n\nDCNS is also developing second-generation hydrogen fuel cell AIP modules for future Scorp\u00e8ne models.\n\n==Scorp\u00e8ne information leak==\n\nIn mid-August 2016, ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper reported that design details of the Scorp\u00e8ne-class submarine and other ships had been leaked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-submarines-india-australia-idUSKCN10Z04G|title=France's DCNS says India submarine data leak may be 'economic warfare'|last1=Siegel|first1=Matt|last2=Irish|first2=John|date=24 August 2016|work=Reuters|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715014212/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-submarines-india-australia-idUSKCN10Z04G|archivedate=15 July 2017}}</ref> The leaked information spreads over 22,400 pages and includes detailed information about the submarine's combat and stealth capabilities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/secret-data-on-india-s-scorpene-class-submarines-leaked-report/story-PqS96Ob4G5tGY088F07tzH.html|date=24 August 2016|work=Hindustan Times|title=Secret data on Indian Navy's Scorpene-class submarines leaked|last=Laskar|first=Rezaul H|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826185437/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/secret-data-on-india-s-scorpene-class-submarines-leaked-report/story-PqS96Ob4G5tGY088F07tzH.html |archive-date=26 August 2016}}</ref> The leak also included information about noise levels, submarine frequencies and more.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/scorpene-leak-submarine-what-it-reveals-explained-2994954/|last=Stewart|first=Cameron|date=25 August 2016|title=What the Scorpene leak reveals|work=The Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829075024/http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/scorpene-leak-submarine-what-it-reveals-explained-2994954/|archive-date=29 August 2016}}</ref> Despite all the information leaks, [[Indian Navy]] chief [[Admiral]] [[Sunil Lanba]] was quoted as saying that the leaks were being viewed \"very seriously\", but were \"not a matter of much worry\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Scorpene-Leak-serious-not-a-matter-of-worry-says-Navy-Chief/2016/08/30/article3603108.ece |title=Scorpene Leak serious, not a matter of worry, says Navy Chief |work=The New Indian Express |accessdate=2016-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831155618/http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Scorpene-Leak-serious-not-a-matter-of-worry-says-Navy-Chief/2016/08/30/article3603108.ece |archivedate=2016-08-31 }}</ref> The report also suggested that an ex-[[French Navy]] officer working as a sub-contractor for DCNS may have been the source of the leak, and that the leaked data may have been written in France in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/French-ex-naval-officer-behind-Scorpene-leak/articleshow/53851448.cms |title=French ex-naval officer behind Scorpene leak? |work=The Times of India |accessdate=2016-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829212448/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/French-ex-naval-officer-behind-Scorpene-leak/articleshow/53851448.cms |archivedate=2016-08-29 }}</ref> However, on 30 August 2016, a court in [[New South Wales]] temporarily banned ''The Australian'' from releasing any more confidential data on the Indian Scorp\u00e8ne-class submarines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/scorpene-leak-the-australian-cant-release-confidential-data-says-court-1451867 |title=Scorpene Leak: 'The Australian' Can't Release Confidential Data, Says Court |last=Som |first=Vishnu |work=NDTV |accessdate=2016-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830161433/http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/scorpene-leak-the-australian-cant-release-confidential-data-says-court-1451867 |archivedate=2016-08-30 }}</ref>\n\n== Operators ==\n\n=== Chile ===\n[[File:Submarino General Carrera (SS-22).jpg|thumb|''Carrera'' of the Chilean Navy]]\nThe [[Chilean Navy]] ordered two Scorp\u00e8ne-class boats, which replaced two {{sclass-|Oberon|submarine|1}}s retired by the Chilean Navy. The Chilean ''Scorp\u00e8ne''-class ''O'Higgins'' and ''Carrera'' were completed in 2005 and 2006, respectively. \n\n=== Malaysia ===\n[[File:Scorpene Tunku Abdul Rahman.jpg|thumb| {{ship|KD|Tunku Abdul Rahman}} of the Royal Malaysian Navy]]\nIn 2002, Malaysia ordered two Scorp\u00e8ne-class boats worth US$1.2 billion. Both boats {{ship|KD|Tunku Abdul Rahman||2}} and ''Tun Abdul Razak'' commissioned by [[Royal Malaysian Navy]] in 2009.\n\n=== India ===\n[[File:First torpedo firing trials of INS Kalvari (S50) - 1.jpg|thumb|{{INS|Kalvari|S21|6}} of the Indian Navy]]\n{{Main|Kalvari-class submarine (2015)}}\nIn 2005, India chose the Scorp\u00e8ne design; purchasing six submarines for US$3 billion (US$500 million per boat). Under a technology transfer agreement, the state-owned Mazagon Docks in Mumbai was to manufacture the submarines, and deliver them between 2012 and 2016,<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-3027893/India-s-Scorpene-submarine-INS-Kalvari-launched-sea-trials.html |title=India's first Scorp\u00e8ne submarine INS ''Kalvari'' launched for sea trials |work=Daily Mail |last=N |first=Ganesh |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=24 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009172941/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-3027893/India-s-Scorpene-submarine-INS-Kalvari-launched-sea-trials.html |archivedate=9 October 2015 }}</ref> however the project is running six years behind schedule.<ref name=\"indianexpress\">{{Cite news |url =https://indianexpress.com/article/india/mazagon-to-deliver-second-scorpene-class-submarine-by-year-end-5344023/ |title =Mazagon Dock to deliver second Scorpene class submarine by year end |date =7 September 2018 |accessdate =28 December 2018 |work =the Indian Express |last =Kulkarni |first =Neha |archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20181205230043/https://indianexpress.com/article/india/mazagon-to-deliver-second-scorpene-class-submarine-by-year-end-5344023/ |archive-date =5 December 2018 |url-status =live }}</ref><ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\">{{Cite news |url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Defence-minister-Arun-Jaitley-reviews-delayed-Scorpene-submarine-project/articleshow/41039868.cms |title =Defence minister Arun Jaitley reviews delayed Scorpene submarine project |date =28 August 2014 |accessdate =24 October 2015 |work =The Times of India |last =Pandit |first =Rajat |url-status =live |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140829015357/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Defence-minister-Arun-Jaitley-reviews-delayed-Scorpene-submarine-project/articleshow/41039868.cms |archivedate =29 August 2014 }}</ref> Construction started on 23 May 2009.<ref name=\"bharat-rakshak.com\"/>  The first Scorp\u00e8ne submarine, named INS ''Kalvari'', was undocked for the purpose of starting sea trials in April 2015 and will be delivered in September 2016.<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\"/> In August 2016, over 20,000 confidential pages of the submarine's manual were leaked by Australian media,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/top-secret-data-on-indias-scorpene-submarine-leaked-says-report-1449447|title=The $3.5 Billion Leak: Scorpene Submarines Exposed, India Assesses Damage|last=Som|first=Vishnu |work=NDTV |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826214321/http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/top-secret-data-on-indias-scorpene-submarine-leaked-says-report-1449447|archivedate=2016-08-26}}</ref> stirring up a controversy about the impact to India's ambitions of fielding a blue-water navy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/india-s-next-generation-of-submarines-are-now-more-vulnerable/story-goZcuLMtwDUGrqlrj4ASuM.html |title=Understanding Scorpene leak: Why India\u2019s next-gen subs are now vulnerable |work=Hindustan Times |last=Joshi |first=Shashank |accessdate=2016-08-26 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826183733/http://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/india-s-next-generation-of-submarines-are-now-more-vulnerable/story-goZcuLMtwDUGrqlrj4ASuM.html |archive-date=2016-08-26 }}</ref>\n\nDCNS answered that those documents were not crucial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/oceanie/fuite-de-documents-chez-dcns-nous-sommes-en-guerre-economique_1824233.html |title=Fuite de documents chez DCNS: \"Nous sommes en guerre \u00e9conomique\" |language=French |accessdate=2016-08-26 |url-status=live |work=L'Express |last=Pommier |first=S\u00e9bastien |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826174926/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/oceanie/fuite-de-documents-chez-dcns-nous-sommes-en-guerre-economique_1824233.html |archive-date=2016-08-26 }}</ref> After extensive sea trials, ''Kalvari'' was commissioned into the Indian Navy on 14 December 2017.<ref name=\"kalvari_inducted\"/>\n\n=== Brazil ===\n[[File:GLAM MB Submarino Riachuelo (46261147032).jpg|thumb|''Riachuelo'' of the Brazilian Navy]]\nIn 2009, Brazil purchased four enlarged Scorp\u00e8nes for US$9.9 billion with a technology transfer agreement and a second agreement to develop a French/Brazilian nuclear-powered submarine. The Brazilian submarine class was given the designation ''Riachuelo'' class. The hull of the first S-BR (''S40'') was laid down at [[Cherbourg]] on 27 May 2010 and is to be jumboized at the Brazilian Navy Shipyard in [[Sepetiba]] in late 2012.<ref name=\"defpro\"/> The latter three submarines will be built there entirely, and are planned to be commissioned in 2020, 2021, and 2022. The nuclear-powered submarine {{ship|Brazilian submarine|\u00c1lvaro Alberto||2}} is under construction since 2018, with scheduled launch for 2027.<ref>{{cite news |title=O Prosub e o submarino nuclear brasileiro SN-BR|url=https://www.naval.com.br/blog/2018/02/20/o-prosub-e-o-submarino-nuclear-brasileiro-sn-br|publisher=Poder Naval|language=pt|date=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Riachuelo'' was launched on 14 December 2018, and began sea trials in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Submarino ''Riachuelo'' inicia provas de mar|url=https://www.naval.com.br/blog/2019/09/25/submarino-riachuelo-inicia-provas-de-mar/|publisher=Poder Naval|language=pt|date=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Potential operators ==\n\n=== Spain ===\nIn 2003, the Spanish government ordered four Scorp\u00e8ne AIP submarines worth \u20ac1,756 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deagel.com/Conventional-Attack-Submarines/Scorpene-Basic-AIP_a000425003.aspx |title=Scorpene Basic-AIP |website=Deagel.com |access-date=24 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923213313/http://www.deagel.com/Conventional-Attack-Submarines/Scorpene-Basic-AIP_a000425003.aspx |archive-date=23 September 2015 }}</ref> However, the Spanish navy canceled the order, and ordered four {{sclass2-|S-80|submarine|0}} submarines, instead. This has caused conflicts and controversies between DCNS and [[Navantia]], as the latter is still involved in the construction of the submarines sold to India, Malaysia, and Chile, while the S-80 is offered on the export market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meretmarine.com/article.cfm?id=108546 |title=Scorp\u00e8ne: DCNS et Navantia en instance de divorce |publisher=Mer et Marine |accessdate=2011-12-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929154438/http://www.meretmarine.com/article.cfm?id=108546 |archivedate=September 29, 2011 }}</ref> As an answer to the competition from the S-80, DCNS designed its own enhanced version of the Scorp\u00e8ne called the {{sclass-|Marlin|submarine|4}}, but little is known about this design and the Scorp\u00e8ne is still offered by France on the export market. The dispute was settled when Navantia gave up export rights on the Scorp\u00e8ne class, leaving DCNS with sole responsibility for the project.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lesechos.fr/12/11/2010/lesechos.fr/020927714393_sous-marins---dcns-et-navantia-reprennent-leur-liberte.htm |title=Sous-marins : DCNS et Navantia reprennent leur libert\u00e9 |language=French |work=Les Echos |last=Ruello |first=Alain |access-date=2017-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009092315/https://www.lesechos.fr/12/11/2010/lesechos.fr/020927714393_sous-marins---dcns-et-navantia-reprennent-leur-liberte.htm |archive-date=2017-10-09 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Poland ===\nOn 1 March 2011, the Naval Shipyard Gdynia of Poland and DCNS offered a license to build a yet undisclosed number of modified Scorp\u00e8ne-class boats. The Scorp\u00e8ne design is competing with that of the German [[Type 214 submarine]].<ref name=\"gw\">{{cite journal | first =S\u0142awomir | last=Sowula | date =March 2011 | title =Gdy\u0144ska stocznia chce budowa\u0107 okr\u0119ty podwodne | journal =[[Gazeta Wyborcza]] | issue =2011\u201303\u201303 | url=http://wyborcza.biz/biznes/1,100896,9192983,Gdynska_stocznia_chce_budowac_okrety_podwodne.html | accessdate =24 October 2015 | language =pl | url-status =live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307155250/http://wyborcza.biz/biznes/1,100896,9192983,Gdynska_stocznia_chce_budowac_okrety_podwodne.html | archive-date =7 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\n=== Norway ===\nIn December 2016, the [[Norwegian Ministry of Defence]] announced that Norway would sign a contract for four new submarines before the end of 2019. These would either be Scorp\u00e8ne vessels from DCNS or German U-boats from [[ThyssenKrupp Marine Systems|ThyssenKrupp]]. Norway would also be looking into possible cooperation on maintenance and construction with other potential buyers of the same submarines, such as Poland or the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regjeringen.no/no/tema/forsvar/innsikt/ubater/nyeubaterstatus/id2522100/|title=Nye ub\u00e5ter - status desember 2016|publisher=Norwegian government|accessdate=9 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110015837/https://www.regjeringen.no/no/tema/forsvar/innsikt/ubater/nyeubaterstatus/id2522100/|archivedate=10 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aldrimer.no/dette-kan-avgjore-ubatkjopet/|title=Dette kan avgj\u00f8re ub\u00e5tkj\u00f8pet|accessdate=9 January 2017|date=9 January 2017|work=aldrimer.no|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110025207/https://www.aldrimer.no/dette-kan-avgjore-ubatkjopet/|archivedate=10 January 2017}}</ref> In February 2017, the Norwegian Government announced that it intended to procure its new submarines from the German manufacturer, ThyssenKrupp. Norway and Germany will buy submarines together to mutualize expenses. In practice the tender was cancelled and exclusive government to government negotiations were initiated.\n\n== Boats ==\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n! Pennant no.  || Name  || Country  || Laid down  || Launched  || Commissioned  || Homeport\n|-\n| SS-23  || ''O'Higgins''  ||  {{CHL}} ||  18 November 1999 || 1 November 2003 || 8 September 2005  || [[Talcahuano]]\n|-\n| SS-22  || ''Carrera''  ||  {{CHL}}  || November 2000  || 24 November 2004 || 20 July 2006  || Talcahuano\n|-\n|  - || {{ship|KD|Tunku Abdul Rahman||6}}  ||  {{MYS}}  || 25 April 2004  || 23 October 2007 || January 2009  || [[Sepanggar]]\n|-\n|  - || KD ''Tun Abdul Razak''  ||  {{MYS}}  || 25 April 2005  || October, 2008 || December, 2009  || Sepanggar\n|-\n|  S-21 || {{INS|Kalvari|S21|6}}  ||  {{IND}}  || 1 April 2009 || 6 April 2015 <ref name=\"myref1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-32193746 |title=New India submarine enters water |accessdate=24 October 2015 |date=6 April 2015 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924163758/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-32193746 |archivedate=24 September 2015 }}</ref>||14 December 2017<ref name=\"kalvari_inducted\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/narendra-modi-inducts-ins-kalvari-into-indian-navy/article21618713.ece|title=Scorpene-class submarine Kalvari, built in Mazagon Dock, inducted into Navy|access-date=2017-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214060305/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/narendra-modi-inducts-ins-kalvari-into-indian-navy/article21618713.ece|archive-date=2017-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/indian-navy-scorpene-submarines-france/1/905375.html|title=Scorpenes no more|access-date=2017-03-20|url-